# Cases and Incidents

This is an overview of the cases and incident sections of GBVIMS+.  ​

Here, we’ll focus on the cases and incidents sections where the data entry occurs.  It’s important to note here that – ​

* Cases are individual cases for case management ​
* Incidents are an individual act of violence as reported by survivors

The GBVIMS+ forms in the cases and incidents sections function just like paper-based forms, they hold the same information.

Before we go in more depth into the cases and incidents sections, let’s talk about the overall navigation.​

Once you are entering data, you will see a left panel navigation list.  This is how you can navigate through the forms.  The titles in the left navigation list are called **Form Groups:**

  ![](data:image/jpg;base64,%)

If a Form Group has only one form, you can simple click on it and it will display the form.  If it has more than one, you can click on the Form Group name or the expand icon to the right of the name to expand it and see all the forms in the group.  Once the form group is expanded you can then click on any of the form names to enter into the chosen form.

### **Sub-forms**

  ![](data:image/jpg;base64,%)

Some forms have sub-forms. To navigate these sub-forms, there is an expand/collapse function, and add or remove functions. ​You will most likely see these sub-forms when an action is commonly repeated, for example follow-up visits, of which there may be multiple. This allows you to add details for each follow-up visit. ​

A field \(data field\) is information within a form.  Fields include examples like name, age, date of birth.​

### Data Fields

​  ![](data:image/jpg;base64,%)![](data:image/jpg;base64,%)![](data:image/jpg;base64,%)

There are a variety of field types including:​

* Text – a short comment​
* Text area – a longer comment box​
* Date – which pulls up a calendar​
* Check boxes ​
* Tick boxes
* Select Drop Down ​
* “Multi-select” - Allows a user to select more than one answer. ​
* Radio Button - “Options” - allows you up to 3 short choices for the radio button values​
* Numeric Value​
* Date Range​

**Help Test** is an option within each field that will allow you to provide some guiding language to give the user a frame of reference for the proper answer - or how to come to a conclusion based on information provided. 

### Cases and Incidents

A case is the case management portion . There can only be one case. Enter a case first.

An incident is the individual incident of violence.​ There can be many incidents. 

  ![](data:image/jpg;base64,%)

To create a new case, click on the cases button on the navigation bar and then click on ‘new case’.​

The benefit of creating the case first and then the incident is that the incident will be pre-populated with the survivor code and other duplicated information from the corresponding case.  ​

### Forms

When creating a NEW CASE you can enter information about the survivor in the cases module. There are 8-10 case management forms.

  ![](data:image/jpg;base64,%)

**Record Owner:** The form is required in the system. It holds the information about what staff member ‘owns’ the case and who was the previous owner. ​Staff don't actually complete this form - info is automatically entered by system. 

**Consent for Services:** This includes information about the survivor’s consent for services. This form is a tick box to ensure that the casework staff received verbal consent for case management services.​

**Survivor Information:** The survivor information form collects demographic information about the survivor such as:

* Case status​
* Name \(and option to hide name\)​
* Survivor code \(only link to incident module\)​
* Age, Date of Birth​
* Sex​
* Country of Origin, Nationality​
* Civil/Marital Status​
* Dependent Information​
* Displacement Status at Time of Report​
* Person with Disabilities​
* Unaccompanied, Separated Child

The information on this form that is also on the intake form will be automatically populated there if you create an incident from inside this case. Any information here that is not needed – for example, you may not collect information about religion in your setting – can be hidden.​Additionally, the name can be entered here, but hidden from anyone besides the casework staff responsible for the case.

  ![](data:image/jpg;base64,%)

The name is meant to only be accessible by the case worker- she alone needs that information. The caseworker after entering the name, can save and click hide \(shown above\). Then the name will be able to be viewed by the caseworker, but will not be able to be seen by the supervisor.​

Even without hiding the name, it is not exportable.

**Survivor Assessment:** The survivor assessment form asks a number of questions about the survivor’s profile, what happened to the survivor and the survivor’s main concerns:

* Survivor profile​
* Survivor context​
* Survivor’s family situation​
* Survivor’s current living situation​
* Survivor’s occupation or role​
* Specific considerations for child survivors​
* Presenting problem​
* Describe what happened to the survivor​
* Key assessment points​
* Current situation and imminent risks​
* Safety needs​
* Health needs​
* Psychosocial needs​
* Legal/justice needs​
* Practical/material needs​
* How long did it take you to complete the assessment

There are also guiding questions that casework staff can answer.​

**Action Plan:** This is where you document the survivor’s action plan.​ The action plan is the form in the cases section that you will most often return to. This is where you document the survivor’s action plan by type of need and referral pathway. You can add as many action plans – based on type of need- as you need. Staff can request approval form supervisors on case plan as well here. 

* Describe the action plan to address this need​
* Type of Need​
* Did you refer the client for this service?​
* Consent to release information for referrals​
* Appointment Date, Time, Service Provider, Service Location​
* Notes​
* Mandatory reporting​
* How long did it take you to complete the case action plan

**Action Plan Follow-Up:** In the same form group, you can document follow-up visits, including the type of service, dates, action taken and plans for case closure or additional visits. Here as well, you can add as many follow-up forms as needed:

* Type of service​
* Follow-up Date​
* Type of referral service​
* Has action been taken​
* Details about action taken​
* Is there a need for further follow-up visits​
* If yes, when do you recommend the next visit take place?​
* If not, do you recommend that the case be closed?​
* Comments​
* Any new concerns or needs​
* Action meet survivor needs​
* Refer survivor for another appointment​
* How long did it take to complete follow-up​
* Progress made toward goals

**Safety Plan:** Here you can document concerns and resources, preparedness, strategies and emotional health: 

* Safety plan needed​
* Developed with survivor​
* Completion date​
* Identify safety concern​
* Resources​
* Safety Preparedness​
* Safety strategies​
* Steps after leaving

 There are a number of guided questions included here.​

**Consent for Referrals:** This is where you can document if a survivor consented to share information for the purpose of a referral.​

**Case Closure:** This is where you can document when a case is ready to be closed. You can include details about the closure assessment, and a checklist \(were needs met, safety plan reviewed and case plan completed, and finally a review by the supervisor\). Staff can also request approval from supervisors on this form. The fields you can enter include:

* Case closure date​
* Case status​
* Closure assessment​
* Needs met; Explain​
* Reason for closure​
* Resume services; Explain​
* Case supervisor reviewed closure; Explain​
* How long to complete the case closure

**Client Feedback:** This is where you document the client feedback form after closure of the case. This should be completed after the case closure.

**Other documents:** This is not a form, but an area where you can scan and upload documents for the case \(scanned or word documents as needed\). For example, this might include the consent form if you fill it out on paper.​ Please do not include names in the uploads \(redacted\).

### Features

In this section we will walk through a few functions that are not form data entry, but related to the cases section. 

#### Export cases as a PDF

If you want to have a paper copy of the forms you filled out in the cases section, you can **export case PDF** and print this file for your records. It will print everything in cases section.

#### Refer and Transfer

In the cases section you can also **refer** and **transfer** cases.​

* If you have active cases you can refer \(for a service\) or transfer \(to transfer case management services\) to another service provider.  ​
* If it is within your own organization, this is facilitated by Primero.  If it is to another organization using a different system, this can still be facilitated by Primero. 

For referrals and transfers, select the case\(s\) you want to refer or transfer then click on the anchored header on actions. Then click refer or transfer. If you are referring or transferring within your own organization, you can enter the user’s name, service, and notes and hit submit:

1\)   ![](data:image/png;base64,%)

2\)   ![](data:image/png;base64,%)

To refer or transfer outside your organization \(or to non-Primero users\), you need to generate a PDF or CSV that can be saved and shared. A note here – that this function will export all the case management files. In most cases, you don’t want to provide all the files as this is not in line with the principle of ‘need to know.’ You might want to use this function to document in the system when a referral or transfer was made, but to continue to use other agreed-upon referral forms:

  ![](data:image/png;base64,%)

Once this is completed, the system will automatically save the referral/transfer notes as the last form in the cases section:

  ![](data:image/jpg;base64,%)

Once an referral/transfer was made from or to a caseworker, they can view the history under the _CASE_ tab and then view _Referrals and transfer_. That’s also where they will have to go in order to accept the transfer or inform when the referral was completed \(done\)​:

  ![](data:image/jpg;base64,%)

  ![](data:image/jpg;base64,%)

#### Flags

Flags can be used in the incident and case sections to flag a case for follow up.  You can include a reason and a date. Supervisors can also flag cases for casework staff.  ​

​  ![](data:image/png;base64,%)

  ![](data:image/png;base64,%)

Flagged cases will appear with a flag on the cases or incidents page. You can un-flag a case by clicking on the case and including a reason for unflagging the case. The system will automatically keep a record of flags for each cases or incident.  You can also filter to flagged cases or incidents in the filter panel.

#### Request approval/approve action plan/ case closure

Caseworkers can request approvals of their case action plan or case closure to CM supervisors. CM supervisors can approve it. It will show on their Dashboard.

  

![](.gitbook/assets/image%20%284%29.png)

![](.gitbook/assets/image%20%283%29.png)

![](.gitbook/assets/image%20%285%29.png)

#### How to see that incidents are linked to cases?

​​Once you have created an incident from a case, you can view the link to the incidents by going to _CASES,_ then _ACTION PLAN,_ then _EDIT_. See link\(s\) to incident\(s\) on the top of the form​:

  ![](data:image/jpg;base64,%)

#### Creating an incident from a new case

Once a case is created, you can then create an incident that is linked to that case. In the Anchored Header, there is a Create Incident button that is available to click once you have saved the case. 

  ![](data:image/jpg;base64,%)

Note: if you are using case management forms in the system, it is to your benefit to enter information into the cases section first and then create an incident from inside that cases so the two will be linked and information auto-populated from the case to the incident. When you’re inside any case you can click ‘Create incident’ to create a new incident linked to that case.  Alternatively, if you do not use the case management section and only the incident section, you can click on ‘incident’ then ‘Create Incident.’​

The  incident tab is linked to IR and therefore the need to complete all info for the IR to be populated accordingly.

#### Incident: Form Groups

When creating a NEW INCIDENT you can enter information about the incident in the incidents module. There are 6 forms:

  ![](data:image/jpg;base64,%)

**Record Owner:** The form is required in the system. It holds the information about what staff member ‘owns’ the case and who was the previous owner. This is automatically generated.

**GBV Incident:** This section documents information about the incident. It includes codes, consent for sharing, dates of interview and incident, time of day, type of place and the incident location including:​

* Status ​
* Consent to share non-identifying information​
* Date of Interview​
* Date of Incident​
* Account of incident​
* Stage of displacement at time of incident​
* Time of Day of Incident​
* Incident  Location​
* Type of place incident occurred

**Type of Incident:** This includes the classification tool, harmful traditional practices, money or goods exchanged, abduction, and previous reporting including:

* Type of Violence \(classification tool\)​
* Harmful Traditional Practice​
* Money, Goods, Benefits exchanged​
* Type of Abduction​
* Reported the Incident anywhere else​
* Prior GBV Experience

**GBV Individual Details:** This forms include information about the survivor. You’ll see here if you entered information into the case section first, some if this will be automatically populated for you. Date of birth and cage are connected, so as not to be in conflict:

* Survivor Code​
* Sex​
* Date of Birth​
* Age \(estimated?\)​
* If contextually relevant: ethnicity, nationality, religion​
* Country of Origin​
* Marital Status​
* Disability Type​
* UAM, SC or Other Vulnerable Child

**Alleged Perpetrator:** This includes demographic details like sex, age group, relationship, occupation and we can also capture in GBVIMS+ the information about multiple perpetrators. It is important to enter the primary perpetrator’s information first as that will be exported to the IR. Fields in this form include: 

* Primary Perpetrator?​
* Sex​
* Past GBV by same Perpetrator​
* If contextually relevant: nationality, ethnicity​
* Age Group​
* Relationship to Survivor​
* Main Occupation​
* NEW: Can add information on multiple perpetrators. The first entry should be the primary perpetrator.

**Service Referrals:** Each of the referrals includes the same information as the GBVIMS intake form: response to referral, appointment date and time, service provider \(can opt for a code here if desired\), location, and any other notes.​ You can add as many as you need here.​ Fields in this form include: 

* Referral source​
* Safe House Referral​
* Health/Medical Referral​
* Psychosocial Referral​
* Legal Assistance Referral​
* Police/Security Referral​
* Livelihoods Referral​
* Child Protection Referral

One final note, as you are entering data in the case or incident section, you can save after each form group is entered or save at the end of filling it out.  If you save after each form group, you will have to click edit to add more information.​

NOTE: Make sure to enter information for all referrals. Otherwise, your IR will not be populated.

**Insist on the importance to save form group by form group and note case/incident at once. This will avoid loosing records in case there is a connection issue or other logistical concerns​.**
